      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Reject delete-after-run recurring cron jobs",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n`deleteAfterRun` is a one-shot lifecycle flag, but cron accepted jobs that combined it with recurring schedules. That leaves the scheduler with conflicting semantics: a job can be marked for deletion after a run while also being scheduled to run repeatedly.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThis adds service-level validation so `deleteAfterRun: true` is only accepted for `schedule.kind=\"at\"`. The check runs on both create and update paths, so invalid jobs cannot be added directly or created by patching an existing job.\n\n## User Impact\n\nValid recurring jobs are unchanged. One-shot jobs still default to `deleteAfterRun`. Invalid recurring delete-after-run jobs now fail fast with a clear validation error instead of being persisted as scheduler state.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/gateway/server.cron.test.ts` — 40 passed\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/gateway/server.cron.test.ts -t \"delete-after-run\"` — 2 passed, 18 skipped\n- `node_modules/oxfmt/bin/oxfmt --check src/cron/service/jobs.ts src/gateway/server.cron.test.ts`\n- `node_modules/oxlint/bin/oxlint src/cron/service/jobs.ts src/gateway/server.cron.test.ts`\n- `git diff --check`\n",
